BASIC
 - update-grub: update current grub, needed after installing a new kernel.
   update-grub2 is the same as update-grub, just a simlink. If not available,
   it can be used grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg instead (be sure that
   the path to the grub.cfg file is correct)
 - /etc/default/grub -> default options for grub, this document is editable
   by a human.
 - /boot/grub/grub.cfg -> main autogenerated grub config file, do not edit!
   use this file to check the names of the operating systems installed used
   later in GRUB_DEFAULT
 - check available menuentries in a fancy way:
     awk -F\' '/menuentry / {print $2}' /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
 - grub-emu -> run grub emulator (better run it in non X)
 - grub2-script-check (opensuse/SLES) /etc/default/grub.cfg -> check syntax
 - grub-reboot <menuentry> (ubuntu) or grub2-once (opensuse/SLES) ->
   temporarily reboot to <menuentry> only once, the next reboot, it will boot
   again the default kernel. <menuentry> is the complete text of the menuentry
   name as specified in the GRUB_DEFAULT option.

ENVIRONMENT
 - GRUB_TIMEOUT=10 -> boot default entry in 10 seconds.
 - GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT=0 -> whait the specified numer of seconds before showing
   the grub menu. If a key is pressed while waiting, the menu is displayed
   directly. if GRUB_TIMEOUT=0, the grub menu won't be displayed unless a key
   is pressed.
 - GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT_QUIET=false -> set to true to supress the verbose
   conuntdown while waiting for a key to be pressed befor the grub menu.
 - GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX='' -> Options passed ALWAYS to the linux kernel.
 - GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT='' -> Options passed to the linux kernel ONLY
   during normal boot, not during recovery mode.
 - GRUB_TERMINAL="console serial" -> set the terminals where grub is displayed.
   console shows to the standard console (the monitor) serial shows grub on the
   serial port as configured by GRUB_SERIAL_COMMAND
 - Default grub boot entry:
    - GRUB_DEFAULT='Ubuntu'
    - GRUB_DEFAULT='Advanced options for Ubuntu>Ubuntu, with Linux 5.4.0-45-generic'


SERIAL CONSOLE TYPICAL CONFIGURATION
   GRUB_TIMEOUT=10
   GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT=0
   GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT_QUIET=false
   GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT="console=ttyS0,115200n8 console=tty0"
   GRUB_TERMINAL="console serial"
   GRUB_SERIAL_COMMAND="serial --speed=115200 --unit=0 --word=8 --parity=no --stop=1"




CUSTOM GRUB ENTRY
 - To add a custom grub entry, simply write your own menuentry { } in the
   file /etc/grub.d/40_custom. The scripts listed under /etc/grub.d/* are
   used to build the definitve /boot/grub2/grub.cfg, and the 40_custom is
   intented for custom menuentries.
 - It is a good ide to first copy and paste an example menuentry from
   /boot/grub2/grub.cfg to /etc/grub.d/40_custom and modify it.
 - Example menuentry:
     menuentry 'aleix-4.10.5-bsc+' {                                                                                                                                       
     	load_video                                                                                                                                                    
     	insmod gzio                                                                                                                                                   
     	insmod part_msdos                                                                                                                                             
     	insmod ext2                                                                                                                                                   
     	set root='hd0,msdos1'                                                                                                                                         
     	if [ x$feature_platform_search_hint = xy ]; then                                                                                                              
     	  search --no-floppy --fs-uuid --set=root --hint-bios=hd0,msdos1 --hint-efi=hd0,msdos1 --hint-baremetal=ahci0,msdos1  ce2f89ff-6a08-4578-9a8f-6f03fa89d6bf    
     	else                                                                                                                                                          
     	  search --no-floppy --fs-uuid --set=root ce2f89ff-6a08-4578-9a8f-6f03fa89d6bf                                                                                
     	fi                                                                                                                                                            
     	echo	'Loading Linux 4.10.5-bsc+ ...'                                                                                                                       
     	linux	/vmlinuz-4.10.5-bsc+ root=UUID=b8c78d2c-1d00-417c-a383-c512fdc779e9 quiet cgroup_no_v1=all                                                            
     	echo	'Loading initial ramdisk ...'                                                                                                                         
     	initrd	/initrd-4.10.5-bsc+                                                                                                                                   
     }     
 - Another example
     # search for a partition named "nixos" and store it in the variable nixos
     # then, load the grub config file in ($nixos)/boot/grub/grub.cfg
     menuentry "NixOS" {
         search --set=nixos --label nixos
         configfile "($nixos)/boot/grub/grub.cfg"
     }

CHECK WHICH BOOTLOADER IS IN USE
 - assuming that the botloader is installed in /dev/sda:
    sudo dd if=/dev/sda bs=512 count=1 2>/dev/null | strings | grep -Eoi 'grub|lilo|acronis|reboot'
